<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="23" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="23">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="23">
The most widespread scolopocryptopid, 
<taxonomicName family="Oryidae" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. melanostoma" order="Scolopendromorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="melanostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="23">S. melanostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a Gondwanan species occurring in the Neotropical, Indo-Malay, and Pacific Island regions (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/187525410X12578602960623" author="Chagas-Jr, A" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of Myriapodology" pageId="18" pageNumber="31" pagination="159 - 168" refId="B15" refString="Chagas-Jr, A, 2010. On Scolopocryptops species from the Fiji Islands (Chilopoda, Scolopendromorpha, Scolopocryptopidae). International Journal of Myriapodology 3: 159 - 168, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1163/187525410X12578602960623" title="On Scolopocryptops species from the Fiji Islands (Chilopoda, Scolopendromorpha, Scolopocryptopidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/187525410X12578602960623" volume="3" year="2010">Chagas-Jr 2010</bibRefCitation>
). In Brazil, records place the species primarily in the southeast, but it also occurs in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Amapá">Amapa</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pará">Para</normalizedToken>
. The species was sighted in the Leonardo da Vinci shale cave from the latter state. Accidental in caves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
